with other couples economically.\n## Marriage partners usually have sex in private, unlike most animals.\n## Human ovulation is concealed. Therefore, most human sex is recreational rather than for reproduction. There are very few animals like bonobos and dolphins who show this phenomenon.\n## All women who live past the age of forty or fifty undergo menopause, a complete shut down of fertility.\n# '''The Battle of Sexes:''' Male and female reproductive interests, more often than not, do not collide. While both of them want to further their spread of genes, who wins is decided by three factors:\n## Parental Investment: Females, in general, invest much more than the male. This is especially true for mammals, where females apart from making costly eggs, go through a period of pregnancy and lactation.\n## Alternative Opportunities foreclosed by Child Care: In case of women, it takes almost a 2 year gap between first and second child. Men, on the other hand, have no such binding. In theory, one man can impregnate all the fertile women on the planet in months. Most men commit themselves to child care primarily because the human baby is very vulnerable and it is very hard to rear one by the female alone. However, this is not true for all animals. There are exceptions like orangutans and giraffes where males make no investment and phalaropes and Spotted Sandpipers, where the male does all the child care.\n## Confidence in Parenthood: Women are assured of their parenthood in the child they are rearing. Whereas, men had no sure-fire way before the advent DNA testing.\n# '''Why Don't Men Breastfeed Their Babies:''' The author proposes that men have almost all the physiological need for lactation, it is just that evolution till now haven't necessitated it. He also proposes that such a scene might be common in the future.\n# '''Wrong Time For Love (Recreational Sex):''' Sex is risky and costly. Why then do human beings, unlike most animals, have recreational sex just for fun? Author says there are two theories to explain it: \"Many-fathers\" theory says that concealed ovulation allows women to have sex with many men and create paternity confusion, which then decreases the chances of infanticide. \"Daddy-at-home\" theory says that women entice men to be around, provide and protect, by allowing him to have sex regularly. By combining both, we reach the conclusion that concealed ovulation arose at a time when our ancestors were promiscuous to avoid infanticide (\"many fathers theory\") but once concealed ovulation evolved, the women chose monogamous relationships with good cave-men (\"daddy-at-home theory\").\n# '''What Are Men Good For:''' By studying the societies of New Guinea and Ache, the author questioned what exactly did men contribute in child-care. One argument is protection, but most often that protection is from other men of a different or same tribe. Another argument is providing food and resources. But as studies of the mentioned societies have shown, men on an average bring lesser calories by trying to hunt down large animals than what women bring by simply picking up fruits and vegetables. The author classifies men into two categories: \"provider\" who actually bring food supply to the family and \"show-offs\" who try to hunt down big animals and mostly come empty handed. A woman is much better off marrying a \"provider\", but \"show-offs\" often enjoy higher social status.\n# '''Making More by Making Less (Menopause):''' Menopause makes no sense from an evolutionary perspective. Why would a woman suddenly become infertile, and then remains so for a large part of her life? The author proposes that it is a trade-off. The woman chooses to rear and care for her already born children than to risk bringing another one to life in such an age. She may also care for her grandchildren at such a point. Moreover, older people in traditional societies also provide value in the form of knowledge and wisdom.\n# '''Truth in Advertising (Secondary Sexual Characteristics):''' There are many theories that explain secondary sexual characteristics:\n## Fisher's Runaway Selection Model: Females get attracted to a particular trait that actually supports survival, male of the species grow more and more of that trait until it becomes useless and counter-evolutionary forces act on it. Male muscles might be an example of it. Though controversial, but length of penis can also be a good example. Here, the counter-evolutionary force being length of vagina.\n## Zahavi's Handicap Theory: It proposes that these signals actually handicap the individual, when the opposite sex looks at their success despite the handicap, they are assured that they are not faking. Peacock's tail is an example of that. In human societies, status symbols, like fancy clothes and cars might be an example.Beautiful faces are also an example of it because faces are extremely vulnerable.\n## Truth-in-Advertising Theory: It is similar to Zahavi's theory but it views signals as evolutionary advantage rather than handicap.\n\nSome signals are honest, like male muscles and female fat in breasts and hips. While same mean nothing, like pitch of voice, hair etc. The author also proposes, that fat deposited in women's body are concentrated in breasts and hips because it deceives men into thinking that the women has better lactation abilities and larger birth canal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jareddiamond.org/Jared_Diamond/Why_Is_Sex_Fun.html|title=Why is Sex Fun? The Evolution of Human Sexuality|website=www.jareddiamond.org|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref>\n\n==Publication history==\n''Why Is Sex Fun?'' was published in 1997 by [[Basic Books]], as part of the [[Science Masters series]].{{sfn|Diamond|1997|page=iv}}\n\n==Reception==\n''Why Is Sex Fun?'' received a positive review from the biologist [[Steve Jones (biologist)|Steve Jones]] in ''[[The New York Review of Books]]''. Jones described the book as engaging and interesting. However, he questioned Diamond's treatment of concealed ovulation, finding it inconclusive.{{sfn|Jones|1997|pages=39\u201341}}\n\nThe anthropologist Peter B. Gray and the evolutionary biologist Justin R. Garcia maintained that ''Why Is Sex Fun?'' was one of the best-read books on human sexuality. However, they considered it \"informative but too thin in substance\".{{sfn|Gray|Garcia|2013|pages=xv, 321}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n;Books\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Diamond|first1=Jared |title=Why is Sex Fun? The Evolution of Human Sexuality |publisher=[[Basic Books]] |location=New York |year=1997 |isbn=0-465-03127-7 |oclc= |doi= |accessdate= |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Gray|first1=Peter B. |last2=Garcia|first2=Justin R. |title=Evolution and Human Sexual Behavior |publisher=[[Harvard University Press]] |location=Cambridge, Massachusetts and London, England |year=2013 |isbn=978-0-674-07273-2 |oclc= |doi= |accessdate= |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n;Journals\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Go Milk a Fruit Bat! |last1=Jones|first1=Steve |journal=[[The New York Review of Books]] |volume=44 |issue=12 |year=1997 |doi= |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.nybooks.com/articles/1122 Review by Steve Jones]\n\n{{Evolutionary psychology}}\n{{Jared Diamond}}\n{{Portal bar|Evolutionary biology|Human sexuality}}\n\n[[Category:1997 non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:Basic Books books]]\n[[Category:Biology books]]\n[[Category:Books about evolutionary psychology]]\n[[Category:English-language books]]\n[[Category:Non-fiction books about sexuality]]\n[[Category:Works by Jared Diamond]]\n{{sex-book-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Khan.ae", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added links and corrected grammatical mistakes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Why_Is_Sex_Fun%3F"}
